// KOI Content Extension — modeling rule.
//
// Pack:      KoiContentExtension ("KOI Content Extension") v1.0.0.
// Targets:   the koi_koi_raw dataset produced by the OFFICIAL MARKETPLACE
//            KOI pack v1.2.3 (integration id "KOI", 13 commands).
//            This pack ships NO integration of its own.
//
// DEPENDENCY: the Alerts block below reads columns that only exist because
// the sibling KoiContentExtension PARSING rule promoted them at ingest
// (item_*, device_*, finding_*, alert_type). Without that parsing rule
// 12 of the Alerts mappings silently resolve to null — event.type, alert.name,
// alert.risks, the whole host block (device_id / hostname / os / os_family),
// source.user.username, and the whole resource block (id / name / type /
// sub_type). Only xdm.event.id, alert.description, alert.severity,
// alert.subcategory and the observer block survive without it.
//
// The AUDIT block is very nearly standalone — it reads raw columns for
// everything EXCEPT xdm.target.resource.sub_type, which reads marketplace_api,
// a parsing-rule column. (An earlier version of this comment claimed the Audit
// block was fully standalone; that stopped being true when sub_type was moved
// to the API vocabulary. Corrected 21 July 2026.)
//
// Either way: the two rules MUST be deployed together.
//
// Structure: one MODEL header per dataset, with per-source_log_type
// filter | alter chains underneath (the Okta reference pattern).
//
// Mapping decisions that are deliberate and should survive future edits:
//   * xdm.alert.category is enumerated (XDM_CONST.THREAT_CATEGORY). The Koi
//     OCSF class_name ("Application Security Posture Finding") is free text,
//     so it goes to xdm.alert.subcategory, NOT category. Leaving category
//     unset is correct until a real enum mapping exists.
//   * xdm.alert.severity is a String (there is no XDM_CONST.SEVERITY_*). Koi
//     already emits the canonical ladder (Informational/Low/Medium/High/
//     Critical), so a to_string() passthrough is enough.
//   * marketplace_api / item_marketplace_api -> xdm.target.resource.sub_type on
//     BOTH blocks — the API vocabulary, never the raw short event form. npm /
//     chrome_web_store / vscode are software ecosystems, NOT operating systems,
//     so they must never reach os_family. (Both _api columns are produced by the
//     sibling parsing rule; see the DEPENDENCY note above.)
//   * xdm.observer.name / .unique_identifier fall back to _collector_name
//     because Koi stopped emitting koi_tenant_name / koi_customer_id — see the
//     dated regression note in the Alerts block.
//   * TWO FIELDS ARE DELIBERATELY UNMAPPED, both removed 21 July 2026 after
//     live measurement. Full reasoning is inline at each site; do not re-add
//     either from memory of an older version of this file:
//       - xdm.alert.original_alert_id (was finding_uid) — finding_uid is a
//         POLICY id, 3 distinct across 1,040+ alert rows. Koi supplies no
//         per-alert vendor identifier on this stream, so the field stays empty.
//       - xdm.target.host.fqdn (was alert_hostname) — hostnames contain a dot
//         on 0 of 1,138 rows. They are bare names; xdm.target.host.hostname
//         already carries them correctly.
//     An empty field is a true statement. A populated one that is wrong is a
//     silent cross-source join failure.
//
// 🚨 ALERT ROW COUNTS ARE NOT ALERT COUNTS. The Marketplace integration
// re-sends every still-open alert on every 1-minute fetch cycle, so koi_koi_raw
// holds one row per alert PER FETCH. Measured 21 July 2026:
//   Alerts, last 24 h : 844 rows ->   3 real alerts (281x)
//   Alerts, last 90 d : 1,158 rows -> 317 real alerts (3.7x)
//   Audit,  last 90 d : 20,142 rows -> 20,142 distinct — NO duplication
// The parsing rule promotes koi_notification_id (from
// metadata.notification_event_id) as the ONLY correct dedupe key. Every widget,
// report and playbook that counts alerts must use
// count_distinct(koi_notification_id); a plain count() is wrong by two orders of
// magnitude. XDM has no "this is a duplicate" field to express this in, so it
// cannot be fixed here — it has to be handled by every consumer.
//
// Live-validated 21 July 2026 (90 days, tenant api-ayman.xdr.eu). Row counts
// quoted below were taken by separate queries minutes apart against a dataset
// that grows every fetch cycle, so they range 1,142–1,166 for Alerts and sit at
// 20,142 for Audit; where two figures disagree the larger is simply the later
// reading, not a contradiction. Ratios are stable and are what to trust.
[MODEL: dataset=koi_koi_raw]
filter source_log_type = "Alerts"
| alter
    // ── identity ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // xdm.event.id = _id, NOT koi_event_id. DO NOT CHANGE THIS.
    // _id is an XSIAM-internal column, present and DISTINCT on every alert row
    // (1,048/1,048 at the 21 July 2026 check). koi_event_id
    // (observables[event.id]) is equally populated but has only 20 DISTINCT
    // VALUES across those 1,048 rows — it is a per-scan-batch UUID, so ~52 rows
    // collide on each one. Using it as the XDM event identity would silently
    // merge unrelated alerts. It is still promoted by the parsing rule as a
    // BATCH CORRELATOR and remains queryable as a raw dataset column; it
    // deliberately has no XDM home.
    //
    // _id being per-ROW is correct here and is NOT a dedupe failure. A row IS a
    // distinct XSIAM event, even when three of them describe the same Koi alert.
    // Deduplication happens at query time on koi_notification_id — see the
    // banner at the top of this file. Do not "fix" xdm.event.id by pointing it
    // at koi_notification_id: that would give 317 XDM events sharing ids across
    // 1,048 rows, which is a worse violation of the field's contract.
    xdm.event.id                = _id,
    // NOTE: alert_type has exactly ONE distinct value in 90 days of live data
    // ("policy_violation"), so xdm.event.type is effectively constant here.
    xdm.event.type              = alert_type,
    // ❌ REMOVED 21 July 2026: xdm.alert.original_alert_id = finding_uid.
    // DO NOT RE-ADD IT. finding_uid is the FINDING/POLICY DEFINITION id, not an
    // alert identity. Live, 90 days: 3 DISTINCT VALUES ACROSS 1,040+ ALERT ROWS
    // (1 distinct across the last 6 hours) — 20940 "MCP Servers alerts",
    // 23300 "NPM Block CS", 20907 "yito test". Every alert a policy ever raises
    // shares its finding_uid, so the field was answering "which rule fired",
    // not "which alert is this".
    //
    // This is the SAME defect xdm.event.id above explicitly avoids — the
    // too-coarse-identifier trap was sidestepped in one place and walked into in
    // another. It is now closed in both.
    //
    // The field is REMOVED, not re-pointed, and the two obvious substitutes are
    // both rejected on purpose:
    //   * _id — it is the XSIAM ROW id, already carried by xdm.event.id. It is
    //     not "original" in any sense: XSIAM minted it, Koi never saw it.
    //     original_alert_id means "the id the VENDOR gave this alert".
    //   * koi_notification_id — it is a NOTIFICATION/delivery id, correct for
    //     deduplication and used for exactly that, but it is not the vendor's
    //     alert identifier either.
    // Koi supplies NO per-alert vendor identifier on this stream. The honest
    // representation of "we do not have one" is an unmapped field. A populated
    // field that silently lies costs more than a null one — a cross-source join
    // on original_alert_id would have collapsed 1,040 alerts onto 3.
    // finding_uid remains a queryable raw dataset column (promoted by the
    // parsing rule) and is the right thing to group by when you want per-policy
    // alert volume.
    xdm.alert.name              = finding_title,
    xdm.alert.description       = message,
    xdm.alert.severity          = to_string(severity),
    xdm.alert.subcategory       = class_name,
    // Degenerates to ["policy_violation", <risk_level>] on current data —
    // see the alert_type note above.
    xdm.alert.risks             = arraycreate(alert_type, risk_level),
    // ── target host (the device the item is installed on) ──────────────
    xdm.target.host.device_id   = device_id,
    xdm.target.host.hostname    = alert_hostname,
    // ❌ REMOVED 21 July 2026: xdm.target.host.fqdn = alert_hostname.
    // DO NOT RE-ADD IT. The value is not an FQDN and never was. Live check:
    // alert_hostname CONTAINS A DOT ON 0 OF 1,138 ALERT ROWS (re-confirmed at
    // 0 of 1,158 during this pass, split 0/858 mcp_server and 0/296 extension).
    // The values are bare NetBIOS-style or human-chosen machine names —
    // "M-HFQQ44F5XF", "Gary的MacBook Air" — and the dot count is zero in every
    // cut of the data: by OS (mac 0/962, linux 0/140, windows 0/70) and by item
    // type alike. This is a property of the feed, not of one cohort.
    //
    // Mapping a bare hostname to fqdn is WORSE than leaving the field null: a
    // cross-source correlation that joins on fqdn will silently fail to match
    // the same machine reported by a source that does supply a real FQDN, and
    // it fails quietly, producing a smaller answer rather than an error.
    // xdm.target.host.hostname above already carries this value correctly and is
    // the field the data actually satisfies. Koi does not supply a domain
    // component on this stream, so there is nothing to build an FQDN from.
    xdm.target.host.os          = device_os_obs,
    // Live-confirmed exhaustive, zero fall-through to the null default.
    // RE-MEASURED 21 July 2026 on the current population (the earlier reading
    // "linux 140 / mac 104 / windows 70 = 314/314" is stale):
    //   mac 962 · linux 140 · windows 70 = 1,172/1,172 rows mapped.
    // The mac share grew because the MCP cohort that now dominates ingestion is
    // mac-heavy — the branch set is unchanged and still complete.
    // The literal for macOS is exactly "mac". Do not "tidy" these branches.
    xdm.target.host.os_family   = if(device_os_obs = "windows", XDM_CONST.OS_FAMILY_WINDOWS,
                                     device_os_obs = "mac",     XDM_CONST.OS_FAMILY_MACOS,
                                     device_os_obs = "linux",   XDM_CONST.OS_FAMILY_LINUX,
                                     to_string(null)),
    // ── user (last logged-on user on that device) ──────────────────────
    xdm.source.user.username    = device_last_user,
    // ── target resource (the flagged item / MCP server) ────────────────
    // id: item_id, plain. The custom pack used
    //     coalesce(item_id, to_string(mcp_id)); that fallback is DEAD CODE —
    //     item_id is non-null AND non-empty on every alert row including all
    //     878 mcp_server rows (re-verified 21 July 2026 on the population that
    //     is now 75% MCP, i.e. exactly the cohort the fallback was written for),
    //     so it never fires and mcp_id never reached XDM anyway. mcp_id stays
    //     available as a promoted dataset column.
    // name: item_id, plain. The custom pack used
    //     coalesce(mcp_package_name, item_id); also dead — mcp_package_name
    //     equals item_id on 878/878 MCP rows, so the coalesce never changed the
    //     result. Stated plainly rather than dressed up as a preference.
    xdm.target.resource.id      = item_id,
    xdm.target.resource.name    = item_id,
    // Two values only. ⚠️ THE SPLIT HAS INVERTED — corrected 21 July 2026 from
    // a stale "extension (296) | mcp_server (18)":
    //   mcp_server 878 rows | current, effectively 100% of live ingestion
    //   extension  296 rows | LAST SEEN 2026-07-09, nothing for 12 days
    // Anything downstream that assumed "mostly extensions" is now backwards.
    xdm.target.resource.type    = item_type,
    // sub_type = the software ECOSYSTEM. This replaces the custom pack's
    // mcp_type (local|remote), which is a network locality, not a sub-type of
    // the resource, and which was inconsistent with the Audit block's
    // marketplace -> sub_type mapping. mcp_type is still promoted by the
    // parsing rule and queryable on the raw dataset.
    //
    // CHANGED 21 July 2026: item_marketplace_api, NOT item_marketplace.
    // The raw event value is a SHORT display form (chrome, vsc, software_windows)
    // that the Koi API rejects with HTTP 400; item_marketplace_api is the same
    // fact in the API's own vocabulary (chrome_web_store, vscode, windows) —
    // see the mapping and its evidence in the sibling parsing rule.
    // sub_type is a cross-source normalised field: it must carry ONE stable
    // vocabulary, and the API's is the one that is documented, enumerated in
    // Koi.yml, and directly usable as a command argument. A dashboard that wants
    // the display form still has item_marketplace on the raw dataset.
    // Coverage is UNCHANGED by this switch: on live data item_marketplace_api is
    // non-null on exactly the same 296 alert rows as item_marketplace
    // (npm 293 -> npm, chrome 3 -> chrome_web_store), null on the 878 mcp_server
    // rows, which carry no item.marketplace observable. Nothing is lost.
    //
    // ⚠️ THIS FIELD IS NULL ON ALL CURRENT DATA — and that is NOT a bug.
    // Corrected 21 July 2026 from a stale "the 18 MCP alerts". Coverage is 296
    // of 1,174 rows (25%), and the extension cohort that supplies those 296 has
    // sent nothing since 2026-07-09. The mapping is KEPT: it is correct, and the
    // cohort may return the moment an extension policy fires again. Do not
    // delete it on the evidence of a 24-hour query, and do not paper over it
    // with resources[mcp].data.marketplace — that field is the empty string on
    // 843 of 854 MCP rows (see the parsing rule).
    // If an unmappable value (built_in / side_loaded / ollama) ever reaches an
    // alert, sub_type is deliberately NULL rather than a value that is not in the
    // vocabulary the field claims to hold.
    xdm.target.resource.sub_type = item_marketplace_api,
    // ── observer (Koi as the detecting product) ────────────────────────
    xdm.observer.vendor         = _vendor,
    xdm.observer.product        = _product,
    // ── tenant (which KOI customer this event belongs to) ──────────────
    // ⚠️ REGRESSION, STILL ACTIVE — RE-CHECK THIS. Koi has stopped emitting
    // koi_tenant_name and koi_customer_id. RE-MEASURED 21 July 2026, superseding
    // the first reading of the same day (which was 430/314 and 20,170/19,984 —
    // same story, smaller window):
    //   Alerts, last 90 days :  1,176 rows,    314 carry both fields (27%).
    //   Alerts, last 24 hours:    862 rows,      0 carry either field.
    //   Audit,  last 90 days : 20,142 rows, 19,885 carry both fields (98.7%).
    //   Audit,  last 24 hours:    257 rows,      0 carry either field.
    // The 24-hour rows are a strict subset of the 90-day rows that lack the
    // fields — every row missing them is recent and every older row has them, so
    // the cut-over is sharp, not a gradual drop-off. The alert percentage looks
    // far worse than the audit one only because the Alerts stream is duplicated
    // (see the banner at the top of this file): the 862 recent alert rows are 3
    // real alerts re-sent, not 862 events lost.
    // NOTE the absolute count of populated ALERT rows has not moved at all —
    // 314 then, 314 now — which is the cleanest possible confirmation that the
    // field simply stopped arriving on a date and nothing since has carried it.
    //
    // The mapping is NOT deleted: the historical rows depend on it and the
    // Koi-side change may be transient. A third argument is appended instead.
    //
    // FALLBACK = _collector_name, the XSIAM event-collector (integration
    // instance) name. Chosen on evidence, not convenience:
    //   * populated 1,176/1,176 alert rows and 20,142/20,142 audit rows over
    //     90 days, and 862/862 + 257/257 in the last 24 hours — 100%, both
    //     blocks, both eras (re-measured 21 July 2026);
    //   * it PRESERVES THE PARTITION the lost field carried. One instance holds
    //     one Koi API key, so one instance = one Koi tenant. Live values line up
    //     one-for-one and even share the string: koi_tenant_name "plts" <->
    //     _collector_name "KOI_PLTS" (18,413 rows), "paet" <-> "KOI_PAET"
    //     (1,885 rows). Nothing else on the row does this — VERIFIED_FACTS §2
    //     notes the pack ships no field identifying the producing instance;
    //     _collector_name is that field, supplied by XSIAM rather than by Koi.
    //   * _vendor / _product were REJECTED as the fallback. They are also 100%
    //     populated but constant ("koi" / "koi"), so they would fill the field
    //     with a value that distinguishes nothing — cosmetically non-null,
    //     operationally useless. They are already mapped, correctly, to
    //     xdm.observer.vendor / .product just above.
    // Cost of the fallback, stated plainly: on recent rows xdm.observer.name
    // changes case and prefix ("KOI_PLTS" not "plts"), so a query grouping over
    // a window that spans the cut-over sees two labels for one tenant. That is
    // strictly better than one label and a null, and it is visible rather than
    // silent — which is the point.
    xdm.observer.name              = coalesce(koi_tenant_name, koi_customer_id, _collector_name),
    // Same fallback. unique_identifier is only required to be stable and unique
    // per observer; the collector name is both, within this XSIAM tenant. On
    // recent rows name and unique_identifier therefore coincide — honest, since
    // the Koi customer id is genuinely unknown for those rows.
    xdm.observer.unique_identifier = coalesce(koi_customer_id, _collector_name);

// ── Audit block ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Koi audit events are FLAT (no observables/resources). This block consumes
// ZERO parsing-rule output; it reads raw columns only. Mapping mirrors the
// AWS-CloudTrail / Monday audit->XDM patterns:
//   * event.operation          — normalised CRUD enum from `action`.
//   * event.operation_sub_type — the raw verb, kept verbatim.
//   * event.original_event_type— the raw vendor `type` (extensions/devices/…).
//   * source.user.user_type    — SERVICE_ACCOUNT for the "Koi" system actor.
//   * target.resource.*        — the object acted on (item/policy/guardrail).
//   * target.host.*            — the managed device (85% of rows carry one).
filter source_log_type = "Audit"
| alter
    // _id is present and distinct on every audit row (20,142/20,142,
    // re-measured 21 July 2026). Koi also emits its own `id` UUID, equally
    // complete and ALSO 20,142 distinct — which is the positive control proving
    // the Audit stream carries NO duplication, unlike Alerts. _id is used here
    // for consistency with the Alerts block.
    xdm.event.id                  = _id,
    xdm.event.type                = action,
    xdm.event.original_event_type = type,
    xdm.event.operation_sub_type  = action,
    xdm.event.description         = message,
    // Operation coverage was 17,233/20,215 (85.3%) with the custom pack's
    // chain; the four branches marked ADDED close all but 8 of the null rows.
    // RE-MEASURED 21 July 2026 by running this exact if() chain live:
    // 20,134 of 20,142 rows map (99.96%) — the ratio is unchanged and the
    // 8 unmapped rows are still the same 8.
    //   archived               2,969 rows — the 4th-largest action overall.
    //   unarchived                 2 rows.
    //   email_sent                 2 rows.
    //   allowlist_items_added      1 row.
    // JUDGEMENT CALL: `archived` -> DELETE. Koi archiving is a soft delete of
    // a device record (the device stops being managed and disappears from
    // inventory views), and `unarchived` exists as the inverse. If your
    // convention treats archive as a state change rather than a removal,
    // switch it to OPERATION_TYPE_UPDATE — it is 2,969 rows either way, so
    // decide deliberately rather than inheriting this.
    // Still null after this chain: the 8 approval_requests rows, where the
    // raw `action` column itself is NULL. Nothing to map there.
    xdm.event.operation = if(
        action = "created",      XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_CREATE,
        action = "installed",    XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_CREATE,
        action = "email_sent",   XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_CREATE,              // ADDED
        action = "updated",      XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_UPDATE,
        action = "enabled",      XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_UPDATE,
        action = "disabled",     XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_UPDATE,
        action = "unarchived",   XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_UPDATE,              // ADDED
        action = "allowlist_items_added", XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_UPDATE,     // ADDED
        action = "uninstalled",  XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_DELETE,
        action = "archived",     XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_DELETE,              // ADDED
        action ~= "(?i)remediation.*", XDM_CONST.OPERATION_TYPE_EXECUTION,
        to_string(null)),
    // No explicit success/fail flag in Koi audit; default SUCCESS, but keep
    // the failure regex so a future failure verb is caught automatically.
    // Live: resolves SUCCESS on every audit row (20,142/20,142 as of
    // 21 July 2026) — the regex never matches because no failure action exists
    // in this data. Unvalidatable here.
    xdm.event.outcome = if(action ~= "(?i).*(failed|error|deny|denied|reject).*",
                          XDM_CONST.OUTCOME_FAILED, XDM_CONST.OUTCOME_SUCCESS),
    // Actor (initiator).
    xdm.source.user.username  = triggered_by,
    // Keyed on triggered_by ALONE, not on category.
    // The custom pack used: if(category = "user" and triggered_by != "Koi",
    // REGULAR, SERVICE_ACCOUNT). That misclassified 22 rows which carry
    // category="system" but a real @paloaltonetworks.com address in
    // triggered_by (aarias@ 9, jegarcia@ 4, ydujardin@ 3, …) as
    // SERVICE_ACCOUNT. `category` describes the audit CHANNEL, not the actor.
    // Verified this change is safe for the large cohort: the 2,968 rows with
    // category="user" AND triggered_by="Koi" (the bulk `archived` device
    // events) still land as SERVICE_ACCOUNT here, because the test is now
    // exactly triggered_by = "Koi".
    xdm.source.user.user_type = if(triggered_by = "Koi",
                                   XDM_CONST.USER_TYPE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT,
                                   XDM_CONST.USER_TYPE_REGULAR),
    // Target object acted upon.
    xdm.target.resource.id       = object_id,
    xdm.target.resource.name     = object_name,
    xdm.target.resource.type     = object_type,
    // Ecosystem. CHANGED 21 July 2026 alongside the Alerts block: marketplace_api,
    // not marketplace, so that ONE XDM field does not carry TWO vocabularies.
    // Leaving this as the raw `marketplace` while the Alerts block emits the API
    // form would put "chrome" and "chrome_web_store" into the same field for the
    // same ecosystem — the exact confusion this pack exists to remove.
    // Live effect, measured on 20,170 audit rows over 90 days (21 July 2026;
    // re-measured later the same day at 13,800 populated of 20,142 — the counts
    // drift with ingestion, the proportions do not):
    //   populated 13,849 -> 13,015. The 834-row difference is deliberate and is
    //   entirely built_in (828), ollama (5) and side_loaded (1). built_in and
    //   side_loaded are installation_method values leaking into the marketplace
    //   field, and ollama is not in the API's marketplace list at all; none of
    //   the three is a software ecosystem, so none belongs in this field.
    //   7,136 rows (52% of the populated ones) CHANGE value — software_windows
    //   -> windows 5,294, chrome -> chrome_web_store 891, software_mac -> mac 617,
    //   vsc -> vscode 175, github -> github_mcp_registry 65, edge -> edge_add_ons
    //   48, firefox -> firefox_add_ons 19, npp -> notepad++ 12, openvsx ->
    //   open_vsx_registry 10, jet -> jetbrains 5. pypi/npm/homebrew/chocolatey/
    //   cursor/docker/claude_desktop_extensions are spelled the same and do not move.
    // The verbatim event value remains queryable as the raw `marketplace` column.
    xdm.target.resource.sub_type = marketplace_api,
    // Managed device (present on item events; null for policy/guardrail).
    xdm.target.host.hostname  = hostname,
    // Observer — Koi as the auditing product.
    xdm.observer.vendor  = _vendor,
    xdm.observer.product = _product,
    // Tenant. ⚠️ Same regression as the Alerts block — full rationale and the
    // reason for choosing _collector_name over _vendor/_product is documented
    // there; do not change one block without the other.
    // Audit-side numbers, RE-MEASURED 21 July 2026 (supersedes the earlier
    // 20,170 / 19,984 / 186 reading of the same day):
    //   last 90 days : 20,142 rows, 19,885 carry koi_tenant_name/koi_customer_id.
    //   last 24 hours:    257 rows,      0 carry either.
    //   _collector_name  : 20,142/20,142 and 257/257 — 100% in both windows.
    // The 257 rows missing the Koi fields are exactly the last-24-hour rows.
    xdm.observer.name              = coalesce(koi_tenant_name, koi_customer_id, _collector_name),
    xdm.observer.unique_identifier = coalesce(koi_customer_id, _collector_name);
